          "type": "passage",
          "title": "Solubility of Solids.",
          "content": [
              {
                  "textLeft": "Some solids dissolve in liquids and form a <b>solution</b>."
              },
              {
                  "image": "g4.s.solids-liquids-gases-e2.sc1_cbse/img/salt-569ce4b4e3-450x331.mp4"
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "For example, when salt is added to water, it breaks up into <b>molecules</b> and spreads into the space between water molecules, forming a solution.<br><br>Any solid matter that dissolves in liquid is called a <b><font color=\"#e80000\">solute</font></b> while the liquid in which it dissolves is called  <b><font color=\"#348ffa\">solvent </font></b>.<br><br>The resulting mixture (solute + solvent) is known as a <b><font color=\"#ffa500\">solution</font></b>."
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "But when we add chalk powder into water, it does not dissolve."
              },
              {
                  "image": "g4.s.solids-liquids-gases-e2.sc1_cbse/img/chalk-in-water-dd7e52ba52-450x219.jpg"
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "This indicates that chalk is a water insoluble substance."
              },
              {
                  "subHeading": "Solubility of Liquids."
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "Some liquids which mix with each other are called <b>miscible liquids</b>."
              },
              {
                  "image": "g4.s.solids-liquids-gases-e2.sc1_cbse/img/coffee-milk-3cbebc0ed8-450x300.mp4"
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "For example, when milk is added to coffee decoction (coffee boiled in water), it easily mixes with it.<br><br>Thus, milk is miscible with water."
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "While liquids which do not mix with each other are called <b><font color=\"#ffcd02\">immiscible liquids</font></b>."
              },
              {
                  "image": "g4.s.solids-liquids-gases-e2.sc1_cbse/img/oil-water-846500591d-450x253.mp4"
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "For example, when oil is added to water, it forms a separate layer as oil is lighter than water and does not mix with it."
              },
              {
                  "subHeading": "Solubility of Gases."
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "Some gases dissolve in water or can be dissolved under pressure."
              },
              {
                  "image": "g4.s.solids-liquids-gases-e2.sc1_cbse/img/sea-animals-29183a6551-450x253.mp4"
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "Aquatic animals breathe in <b><font color=\"#348ffa\">oxygen</font></b> dissolved in water."
              },
              {
                  "image": "g4.s.solids-liquids-gases-e2.sc1_cbse/img/coca-cola-2da4eeefbb-450x252.mp4"
              },
              {
                  "textLeft": "Aerated cold drinks contain <b>carbon dioxide</b> dissolved under pressure.<br><br>When cold drink is poured out, this gas fizzes out in the form of bubbles."
              }
          ],
